forecast_sql_generation_prompt = """
Using ONLY the steps from Phase 1, generate ONE combined PostgreSQL query.

SQL rules (MANDATORY):
- Query must start with SELECT or WITH ONLY
- All tables must be referenced as finance.forecast_data_new
- ALL column names AND aliases MUST be enclosed in double quotes
  CORRECT: SELECT "amount" AS "Revenue"
  WRONG:   SELECT "amount" AS Revenue
- When using ROUND(), ALWAYS cast using ::numeric AFTER dividing by 1000000.0
  CORRECT: ROUND((SUM(COALESCE("amount",0))/1000000.0)::numeric, 2)
  WRONG:   ROUND(CAST(SUM("amount")/1000000.0 AS numeric), 2)
  WRONG:   ROUND(SUM("amount")::numeric/1000000, 2)
- Display format: "$123.45M" always. NEVER raw numbers.
- The SQL MUST NOT contain any of the following keywords:
  DROP, DELETE, TRUNCATE, ALTER, UPDATE, INSERT, CREATE, REPLACE, GRANT, REVOKE
- No comments inside SQL
- Never tag the column name with finance.forecast_data_new
  WRONG: SELECT finance.forecast_data_new."l6_description"
  CORRECT: SELECT "l6_description" FROM finance.forecast_data_new
- Use NULLIF for divide-by-zero protection, not CASE WHEN <> 0
  CORRECT: x / NULLIF(y, 0)
  WRONG:   CASE WHEN y <> 0 THEN x / y ELSE NULL END
- GROUP BY must list ONLY bare column names, never expressions or conditions
- NULL in UNION ALL: ALWAYS cast NULL::text or NULL::numeric. NEVER bare NULL.
- Keep SQL simple, readable, and valid PostgreSQL
- ONE SQL statement only. NEVER multiple SELECTs.
- NO additional GROUP BY beyond what is explicitly requested.

=====================================================
OVERALL TASK STRUCTURE — THREE PHASES (MANDATORY)
=====================================================

-----------------------------------------------
PHASE 1 — LOGICAL PLANNING (NO SQL)
-----------------------------------------------
1. Carefully read the user question and schema.
2. Break the requirement into clear, sequential logical steps.
3. Each step must describe WHAT needs to be calculated, filtered, grouped, or compared.
4. Do NOT generate SQL in this phase.
5. Output steps as short, precise statements.

-----------------------------------------------
PHASE 2 — SQL CONSTRUCTION
-----------------------------------------------
Using ONLY the steps from Phase 1, generate ONE complete PostgreSQL query.

=====================================================
COLUMN REFERENCE (ALL VALID COLUMNS)
=====================================================
"version", "amount", "Year", "month",
"entity_name", "ems_id", "opportunity_id",
"ruc_risk", "attrition_description",
"product_combo", "ora_account", "location",
"ora_company", "cost_center", "icp_hfm",
"product_description",
"l4_description", "l5_description", "l6_description",
"l7_description", "l8_description",
"l7_account", "l8_account", "l9_account", "l10_account"

"Year" is ALWAYS uppercase integer (e.g. 2026).
"month" is VARCHAR: 'Jan','Feb','Mar','Apr','May','Jun','Jul','Aug','Sep','Oct','Nov','Dec'
NEVER use integers for month. NEVER use DATE_TRUNC.

=====================================================
VERSION RULES
=====================================================
Version column: "version". Values: '1+11','2+10','3+9','4+8' etc.
Number BEFORE + = actual months. Higher = more recent. 3+9 > 2+10 > 1+11.

DEFAULT (user does not specify version):
WHERE "version" = (
    SELECT "version" FROM finance.forecast_data_new
    ORDER BY CAST(SPLIT_PART("version",'+',1) AS INTEGER) DESC LIMIT 1
)

LATEST version subquery:
(SELECT "version" FROM finance.forecast_data_new
 ORDER BY CAST(SPLIT_PART("version",'+',1) AS INTEGER) DESC LIMIT 1)

PRIOR version subquery:
(SELECT "version" FROM finance.forecast_data_new
 ORDER BY CAST(SPLIT_PART("version",'+',1) AS INTEGER) DESC LIMIT 1 OFFSET 1)

VERSION COMPARISON — ALWAYS use CASE WHEN, NEVER IN() for two versions:
SUM(CASE WHEN "version"='2+10' THEN COALESCE("amount",0) ELSE 0 END) AS "latest"
SUM(CASE WHEN "version"='1+11' THEN COALESCE("amount",0) ELSE 0 END) AS "previous"

ONLY generate comparison when user says "compare","vs","variance","difference".
Otherwise filter single version only.

=====================================================
YEAR RULES
=====================================================
FY26/2026 -> "Year"=2026 (integer, uppercase "Year").
Not stated -> "Year"=(SELECT MAX("Year") FROM finance.forecast_data_new).
EVERY CTE and subquery MUST include "Year" filter.

=====================================================
QUARTER RULES
=====================================================
No "quarter" column exists. Derive from "month":
Q1 -> "month" IN ('Jan','Feb','Mar')
Q2 -> "month" IN ('Apr','May','Jun')
Q3 -> "month" IN ('Jul','Aug','Sep')
Q4 -> "month" IN ('Oct','Nov','Dec')

For quarterly grouping use:
CASE WHEN "month" IN ('Jan','Feb','Mar') THEN 'Q1'
     WHEN "month" IN ('Apr','May','Jun') THEN 'Q2'
     WHEN "month" IN ('Jul','Aug','Sep') THEN 'Q3'
     WHEN "month" IN ('Oct','Nov','Dec') THEN 'Q4' END AS "quarter"

Monthly ORDER BY: ALWAYS CASE WHEN 'Jan' THEN 1 ... 'Dec' THEN 12. NEVER alphabetical.

=====================================================
ACCOUNT / REVENUE TYPE RULES
=====================================================
"l7_account" separates Revenue and Operating Expenses.
Revenue -> "l7_account" = 'Revenue'
Operating Expenses -> "l7_account" = 'Operating Expenses'

For specific account sub-types use "l8_account":
"recurring" -> "l8_account" = 'Recurring Revenue'
"non-recurring" -> "l8_account" = 'Non-Recurring Revenue'
Any other account -> "l8_account" = '[exact user value]'
NEVER use "l6_description" or any other column for this.

=====================================================
EBITDA RULES
=====================================================
EBITDA  = Revenue - Operating Expenses
EBITDA% = EBITDA / Revenue * 100

ALWAYS return ALL FOUR columns together:
Revenue | Operating Expenses | EBITDA | EBITDA%

Use SUM(CASE WHEN "l7_account"=...) to derive Revenue and Operating Expenses in ONE scan.
NEVER filter WHERE "l7_account" when BOTH are needed.

=====================================================
ATTRITION RULES
=====================================================
Filter: "attrition_description". EXACT DB values (case-sensitive):
'Known attrition'  'Specific attrition'  'attrition provision'
NEVER use LOWER()/UPPER(). NEVER title-case.

=====================================================
RUC / RISK RULES — CRITICAL
=====================================================
When user asks for RUC revenue:
WHERE "ruc_risk" = 'RUC'
AND ("attrition_description" IS NULL OR TRIM("attrition_description") = '')

When user asks for Risk ID revenue:
WHERE "ruc_risk" = 'Risk ID'
AND ("attrition_description" IS NULL OR TRIM("attrition_description") = '')

When user asks for Risk UID revenue:
WHERE "ruc_risk" = 'Risk UID'
AND ("attrition_description" IS NULL OR TRIM("attrition_description") = '')

ALWAYS add the attrition_description IS NULL filter for RUC/Risk queries. No exceptions.

=====================================================
VARIANCE QUERIES — MANDATORY BEHAVIOR
=====================================================
When user asks for variance, delta, difference, or comparison:

1. ALWAYS return these columns:
   [group-by col] | Latest ($M) | Previous ($M) | Variance ($M) | Variance %

2. VARIANCE DIRECTION:
   Revenue  : Latest - Previous  (positive = revenue went up)
   OpEx     : Previous - Latest  (REVERSED — positive = costs went down)
   EBITDA   : Latest - Previous
   EBITDA%  : Latest EBITDA% - Previous EBITDA% (percentage points)

3. VARIANCE % formulas:
   Revenue  : Variance / Previous Revenue
   OpEx     : Variance / Latest OpEx
   EBITDA   : EBITDA Variance / Latest Revenue

4. Use SUM(CASE WHEN "version"=...) to pivot in ONE scan.
5. Column aliases: ALWAYS "latest" and "previous". NEVER "latest_forecast"/"prior_forecast".
6. ORDER BY ABS(variance) DESC for comparisons.

=====================================================
UNION ALL — CRITICAL POSTGRESQL RULES
=====================================================
NEVER put ORDER BY or LIMIT inside any SELECT within UNION ALL.
ALWAYS wrap entire UNION ALL in outer subquery:

WRONG:
SELECT ... GROUP BY ... ORDER BY x LIMIT 10
UNION ALL
SELECT ...

CORRECT:
SELECT * FROM (
    SELECT ... GROUP BY ...
    UNION ALL
    SELECT ...
) t ORDER BY sort_key ASC, x DESC

TOTALS ROW (mandatory every tabular query):
UNION ALL with 'Total'::text in first text column.
sort_key=0 for main rows, sort_key=1 for Total.
Total row uses identical WHERE filters as main query.
NULL in UNION ALL: NULL::text or NULL::numeric ALWAYS.

=====================================================
LIMIT RULES
=====================================================
LIMIT 10 for l4/l5/l6/l7/l8/entity_name grouping.
NO LIMIT for month/quarter/ruc_risk/attrition/version grouping.
LIMIT always at very end in outermost query ONLY.
For top N + Total row: LIMIT N+1 at outer level.
NEVER put LIMIT inside a SELECT that participates in UNION ALL.

=====================================================
SORTING
=====================================================
Variance queries: ORDER BY ABS("variance") DESC LIMIT 100
Non-variance: ORDER BY ABS(<primary metric>) DESC LIMIT 100
Trend queries: sort chronologically by year, month. NEVER apply LIMIT to trends.
User-specified top N: use EXACT N requested.

=====================================================
PRODUCT HIERARCHY
=====================================================
l4_description -> l5_description -> l6_description -> l7_description -> l8_description -> entity_name

PRODUCT FILTERING:
Product name default -> "l8_description". l5/l6/l7 stated -> that exact level only.
NEVER substitute levels.

=====================================================
DRIVERS QUERY — HIGHEST PRIORITY
=====================================================
Triggers: "explain the drivers","drivers of recurring revenue","explain components contributing",
"contributing to change","explain the change","what is driving","breakdown of change",
"RUC and new sales","organic revenue and new sales"

NEVER trigger for plain "what is the variance between X and Y" without driver keywords.

MANDATORY TEMPLATE (substitute [V1],[V2],[Y] from question or use dynamic subqueries):
WITH summary AS (
    SELECT "attrition_description","ruc_risk",
    ROUND((SUM(CASE WHEN "version"=[V1] THEN COALESCE("amount",0) ELSE 0 END)/1000000.0)::numeric,2) AS "latest",
    ROUND((SUM(CASE WHEN "version"=[V2] THEN COALESCE("amount",0) ELSE 0 END)/1000000.0)::numeric,2) AS "previous",
